Citation.sTitle: Influence of NH4Br on Solvation Behavior of Polyhydroxy Solutes in Aqueous Solutions at Different Temperatures and Atmospheric Pressure
Citation.sAbstract: Precise density and viscosity measurements on ternary solutions (polyhydroxy solute + NH4Br + H2O) have been carried out over the temperature range (288.15 to 318.15) K at atmospheric pressure. Partial molar volumes, V2deg at infinite dilution and the Jones-Dole B-coefficients obtained from above data were utilized to estimate the transfer parameters (?tV2deg and ?tB) for polyhydroxy solutes. The interaction coefficients were obtained from the transfer values using the McMillan Mayer theory of solutions. Isobaric expansion coefficients and second-order derivatives {(?V2deg /?T)P, (?2V2deg /?T2)P}, and dB/dT coefficients were also determined to study the effect of temperature. These parameters were used to understand the kosmo-/chaotropic nature of solutes and cosolute which is helpful in rationalizing the mixing effects due to interactions between them in these solutions, concomitantly keeping the stereochemical differences of the polyhydroxy solutes in view.
